@Lohengramm I'll repeat myself: CO2 levels were five times higher during the Jurassic than they are today, even with human emissions. Without human activity digging up and burning fossil fuels that carbon would remain trapped underground where it's not available for use by plants.

Natural processes move carbon underground (over the course of millions of years), and over enough time that could cause atmospheric CO2 levels to drop below the point necessary to sustain plant life. During the last ice age that almost happened when they dipped to around 180 ppm. After millions of years of carbon being depleted from the atmosphere there's no reason to assume preindustrial levels of CO2 are ideal. Climate change could be a change for the better, and you're a long way off from proving your doomsday theory.

According to ASHRAE and OSHA 1000 ppm is safe, compared to 350-450 ppm as the normal outdoor level. Adverse health effects don't set in until 2500-5000 ppm and a maximum allowed concentration within an 8 hour work period is 5000-10000 ppm.

